{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17629878","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17629878"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:10:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:10:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17300"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17300","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17300"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.81,0.16,0.03,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9990"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77308"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9990","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9990"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17300"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62815"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1243"},{"type":"tags","id":"2560"},{"type":"tags","id":"2778"},{"type":"tags","id":"3000"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"6094"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23399"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23403"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77308","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77308"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department after a fall from a bicycle. He landed on his right shoulder and now complains of pain and difficulty moving his right arm. There is tenderness over the right shoulder, and he is unable to abduct his right arm beyond 15 degrees. Sensation over the lateral aspect of the shoulder is reduced.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following nerves is most likely injured?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Axillary nerve","Musculocutaneous nerve","Radial nerve","Median nerve","Ulnar nerve"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe inability to abduct the arm beyond 15 degrees, along with reduced sensation over the lateral aspect of the shoulder, suggests an injury to the \u003Cstrong\u003Eaxillary nerve\u003C/strong\u003E. The axillary nerve innervates the deltoid muscle, which is responsible for abduction of the arm beyond the initial 15 degrees, and provides sensation to the skin overlying the deltoid.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect answers can be explained as follows: \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emusculocutaneous nerve\u003C/strong\u003E primarily innervates the muscles of the anterior compartment of the arm, such as the biceps brachii, and is responsible for flexion of the elbow, not abduction of the arm.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eradial nerve\u003C/strong\u003E is responsible for extension of the wrist and fingers, and sensation over the posterior aspect of the forearm and hand. It does not affect arm abduction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emedian nerve\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily involved in the innervation of the anterior forearm and some intrinsic muscles of the hand, affecting wrist and finger flexion, not arm abduction. Its sensory innervation is the lateral palmar aspect of the hand. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eulnar nerve\u003C/strong\u003E innervates some of the intrinsic muscles of the hand and provides sensation to the medial aspect of the hand. It does not play a role in arm abduction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The axillary nerve is responsible for innervating the deltoid muscle, which is crucial for arm abduction.","Injury to the axillary nerve can result in an inability to abduct the arm beyond 15 degrees.","The radial nerve is primarily responsible for extension of the wrist and fingers."],"references":["Polcaro L, Charlick M, Daly DT. Anatomy, Head and Neck: Brachial Plexus. [Updated 2023 Aug 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK531473/","Sakellariou VI, Badilas NK, Mazis GA, Stavropoulos NA, Kotoulas HK, Kyriakopoulos S, Tagkalegkas I, Sofianos IP. Brachial plexus injuries in adults: evaluation and diagnostic approach. ISRN Orthop. 2014 Feb 9;2014:726103. doi: 10.1155/2014/726103. PMID: 24967130; PMCID: PMC4045362","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62815"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17300"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62815","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62815"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-06T15:49:30+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-06T15:50:04+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9990"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77308"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","